title: For Sale:  German WWll Walther PP Pistol
postcontent: Perfect working order 32 cal. handgun with NSKK swastika logo. Pre PPK issue which puts it in the 1939-1944 period. NSKK is an acronym for the National Socialist Motor Corps, a paramilitary organization of The NAZI party. (Comprehensive info about the NSKK can be had at  < wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Socialist_Motor_Corps >). Gun ia designed for quick field stripping for cleaning. Shows expected wear-usage but no metal defect. Clearly indicates that it was used regularly during the war. Custom, quick-draw holster with clip compartment. The bluing on the emblem is lightened, but clearly visible.  Pistol was taken from a dead officer in the 1945 invasion of Germany. It was pawned at a North Philadelphia liquor store about 1950.

title: For Sale:  U.S. Springfield Model 1795 Cut Down
postcontent:
I found this rifle while cleaning out my father's basement.   I believe I have a U.S. Springfield Model 1795 Musket (Type II or Type III) that has been modified.  It appears to have a percussion cap lock and was cut down to a total length of 42.5 inches.  I think these are referred to as "Indian rifles" or "farmer's rifles".

The area behind the trigger is stamped "1811" but the butt plate is stamped "1812" and it is stamped "U.S. Springfield".  There are no other identifiable markings that I could find.  It appears in pretty good shape (but there is a wedge of wood gouged out in front of the trigger plate).

This gun appears typical of a military musket that has been cut down for "sporting" use after its military use.  This gun indeed started out life as a primary American military flintlock musket made in 1812 which could've been used against the British in the war of 1812.

Originally, these guns were made with barrels measuring about 44 inches with three bands attaching barrel to stock. This gun has also been converted to percussion with a drum type of bolster that could of been performed by numerous gunsmiths, blacksmiths, or other mechanics during the anti-bellum era (1845-1860). These guns were cut down for many 
reasons, reducing weight would make these more amenable for use on a farm to hunt game, etc.  I have an e-mail dated 2011 from a very well known U.S. antique gun dealer who stated that he believed the gun was valued at, because of its condition, at between $600 - $1,000.  I can e-mail additional photos if interested.  REASONABLE offers considered.

title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical PredatAR AR-15 Rifle
postcontent:
Brand new, in the box with all the swag (down to the Dillo Dust for your weekend barbecue), LaRue Tactical PredatAR 5.56 w/ 16 in barrel. Geissele trigger, FDE Magpul furniture, PredatAR Owner's Hat, LaRue's iconic stickers, pocket Constitutions, and FDE hard case. This rifle is a shooter, with its 3 shot group target from the factory measuring .346 MOA. Firm price, cash only deals, please.

XTRAXN™ is a proprietary chamber feature added to reduce frictional forces caused by pressure-expanded cartridge cases bearing against chamber walls. Facilitates reliable extraction through a wide range of temperature / chamber pressure extremes. XTRAXN™ extends extractor life, while having no effect on the firearm's accuracy. All this, and it dovetails well with the OBR's world-famous accuracy.

Specs:
Caliber: 5.56 x 45 mm NATO
Rifle Weight: 6.25 lb. (based on 16.1” barrel version, unloaded without optics)
Barrel Length: 16.1“
Barrel Material: Stainless Steel, Blackened.
Rifling Twist Rate: 1/8
Muzzle Thread Configuration: ½ x 28 *
Gas System: Mid-Length Direct Impingement
Trigger Group: Two-Stage Geissele
Rate of Fire: Semi automatic
Magazine Capacity: 30 rounds

PredatAR® 5.56 Overview:

The PredatAR® 5.56 is designed for those who are searching for a lightweight, ultra-reliable and accurate 5.56 mm NATO rifle for home-defense, competition-shooting or hunting. The PredatAR® takes the highly accurate OBR 5.56 “Lite” design, and lightens it in every possible way with the least possible impact to the accuracy that the standard OBR is known for. By contouring the barrel, skeletonizing the handguard, lowering and simplifying the upper rail, and using a low-profile gas block, we were able to reduce roughly 2 pounds from the standard OBR 5.56 rifle.

The barrels are Stainless Steel, lightweight-profiled, Wylde chambered and feature polygonal rifling in a 1/8 twist rate. All barrels are threaded in ½ x 28, with an A2 flash hider attached* (other muzzle devices can be added at an additional cost).

The handguards on the PredatAR® extend out 14.75”, to suit a larger range of shooting styles. The zero-MOA upper rail provides plenty of room for weapon-mounted night-vision day/night combinations. Both the upper and lower are CNC-machined from billet 7075-T6, for the optimum fit and consistency. Even though we lightened certain features, there is still additional material in strategic areas to achieve maximum accuracy. Each rifle ships with one, 3” long, MIL-STD-1913 detachable rail section.

Both models come with a 6-position Magpul MOE Stock and LaRue medium A-PEG™ Grip. The Bolt Carriers are hand-polished hard-chrome with max-staked carrier keys, with Texas-Spec Bolt assemblies. The lower assembly has the proven Geissele Two-Stage trigger.

(Iron Sights, Optics and QD mounts not included in price)

The Franchi I-12 represents a new line of Franchi auto-loaders by incorporating a free-floating bolt with the Inertia Driven System. title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare FI Industries Model D .380 (Colt Pony)
location: Winston Salem, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
Looking to sell or trade an interesting pistol I came across.  It is a F I Industries Model D .380.  Looks like a mini 1911.  Very nice condition.  From the research I have done, this is a very rare pistol.  I have taken it to two different gun stores and both said they have never seen one before in all the years they have been dealing.

I am no expert and cannot speak to the absolute truth of what I have read, but I found the following information on this pistol from several locations...

"In the 1970's Colt decided to offer a scaled down 1911 in .380 auto and chose to partner with Star instead of making their very own gun (called the Pony).  After this product was announced, Colt, just coming out of bankruptcy, decided to discontinue all of their .380 products.  Very few Colt-branded guns seem to have been sold.  FI Industries bought up the parts and assembled them as the Model D.  The frames were made in anticipation of the Colt deal, as all the early serial numbers start with "CPA (Colt Pony Automatic).

Supposedly there were only around 100 made with the CPA serial numbers (which this one has).  The plaque on the grip says "FI Industries, Washington DC"

Open to offers from those who know more about this pistol and trades.
